# Its tests therefore carry the literal header strings as fixtures — they are
# the pattern the guard rejects, not real key material (the body is the 4-char
# stub `MIIE...`). gitleaks' default `private-key` rule matches the header
# alone, so it flags the very test that proves the guard works.
packages/toolbelt/test/guards.test.ts:private-key:227
